2 players in turn mark 2 numbers.

text:
@KentHaines The exponent "sticks" to whatever it is touching. Here it is only touching the 5. To include the minus, you have to write (-5)^2 so the exponent can stick to both.
It's related to PEMDAS --- exponents do their thing *before* everything but parentheses.

Teachers do have more latitude than most people under copyright law to use materials within their own classrooms. Online or in blog posts, we're in the same boat as everyone else.

text:
@mpershan @mtrushkowsky And your point is also good!
I guess "inspired by" or "influenced by" are what I *hope* I'm doing when I adapt something. But "steal" alludes to how muzzy is the line between legitimate use and intellectual property theft.

text: @mtrushkowsky @mpershan @Trianglemancsd Yes, artists and writers have used this language for ages. But the point is well taken. "Inspired by" is much more accurate. "Adapted from" or "based on" push the limits of copyright, however. We might use these as teachers, but writers/artists can't legally do that.
